data.content:
Here are better MSTest assertions for each case:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Instead of Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows expected vs actual on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.All(...))` | `CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(...)` | Identifies *which* item failed (MSTest 3.8+) |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, x.Count)` | Reports "Expected: 3, Actual: 1" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer failure message |

Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods: `Contains`, `AreEquivalent` (ignores order), `AllItemsAreUnique`, `IsSubsetOf`.

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy` requires MSTest 3.8+. On older versions, use `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))` or loop manually.
